Cement : It doesn't seem to follow a traditional nomral distribution. The model is rightly skewed, with a mean 280 and a high standard deviation of 108. There seems to be no outliers in this dimension. Slag : It seems to have two peaks hence following a bimodal distribution. It is heavily skewed towards right with a mean of 73 and a median of 22. There's an outlier showing relatively less variance. Ash : It is following a bimodal distribution with 50% of the values being zero and a mean of 54. The boxplot displaying only skewness on the right but no outlier. Water : There are multiple peaks on the distribution curve making it a multimodal distribution. The box plot show that it's slightly skewed on the left, there are a few outliers that are present. Superplastic : It is a bimodal distribution, with a skewness on the left but the tails are fat on the postive side with a few outliers existing. It's showcasing a relatively large variance. Coarseagg : It shows the properties of a multimodal distribution. With the box plot there is a slight skewness towards the right witht the mean being higher than the median. And there are no outliers. Fineagg : There are two peaks and according to the definiton it is a bimodal distribution. Thee boxplot show that it is slightly skewed on the left with the mean being lesser than the median, and there is a single outlier existing on the positive side. Age : There are multiple peaks making it a multimodal distribution. The boxplot shows that it is rightly skewed, the mean is higher than the median and having outliers on the positive side. Strength : It is unimodal distribution. It is slightly right skewed witht hte being mean being marinally higher than the median, and it has fatter tails displaying a larger variance

In [19]:
def outliers(x):
    sort_data=np.sort(x)
    q1=x.quantile(0.25)
    q3=x.quantile(0.75)
    iqr=q3-q1
    clean_data = x[~((x < (q1-1.5*iqr)) | (x > (q3+1.5*iqr))).any(axis=1)]
    return clean_data

from sklearn.model_selection import KFold
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score 
def model(mod,x,y):
    x_train,x_test,y_train,y_test=train_test_split(x,y,test_size=.25,random_state=1)
    x_tv,x_val,y_tv,y_val=train_test_split(x,y,test_size=.20,random_state=1)
    
    mod.fit(x_tv,y_tv)
    kf = KFold(shuffle=True, n_splits=5)
    cv_results = cross_val_score(mod, x_train, y_train, cv=kf)#, scoring='clf')
    #print(cv_results.mean())  
    return cv_results.mean()
    #return cv_results.mean()
    #print("mod on test data ",mod.score(x_val,y_val))
